<ns4940:section xmlns:ns4940="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.sed.introduction">

  <ns4941:title xmlns:ns4941="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Introduction</ns4941:title>
  <ns4942:para xmlns:ns4942="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Prior to the wide spread use of <ns4943:emphasis xmlns:ns4943="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Vi</ns4943:emphasis>, <ns4944:emphasis xmlns:ns4944="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Vim</ns4944:emphasis>,
    <ns4945:emphasis xmlns:ns4945="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">emacs</ns4945:emphasis> and other editors, Linux provided a line editor,
    <ns4946:command xmlns:ns4946="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">ed</ns4946:command>, which enabled you to edit line for line. Even though
    <ns4947:command xmlns:ns4947="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">ed</ns4947:command> is virtually no longer used as an editor, it formes the
    basis for <ns4948:command xmlns:ns4948="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">sed</ns4948:command>, the <ns4949:emphasis xmlns:ns4949="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">stream editor</ns4949:emphasis>.
  </ns4942:para>
  <ns4950:para xmlns:ns4950="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Sed enables you to edit files non-interactively, <ns4951:abbrev xmlns:ns4951="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">i.e.</ns4951:abbrev> to run sed with
    a command which tells it which editing tasks it should perform on the target stream.
  </ns4950:para>
</ns4940:section>